12 scaled to annual subcontracting goals that account for both total
13 qualified subcontract labor hours and the ratio of qualified
14 subcontract labor hours to total qualified labor hours. Unless
15 limited by the cost/benefit cost-benefit analysis, the net benefit
16 rate shall:
17 1. Not exceed twenty-five hundredths one-hundredths of one
18 percent (0.25%) when annual qualified subcontract labor hours are
19 less than Two Hundred Thousand Dollars ($200,000.00) or when annual
20 qualified subcontract labor is less than one percent (1%) of the
21 annual total qualified labor hours claimed;
22 2. Not be less than five-tenths of one percent (0.5%) when
23 subcontract goals are met with a minimum of Two Hundred Thousand
24 Dollars ($200,000.00) of annual total qualified subcontractor labor
ENGR. S. B. NO. 1403 Page 13

1 hour s and these hours are a minimum of one percent (1%) of the
